         <lg type="poem.sonnet-shakespearean"><!-- To capture one or more lines of verse, nest <l> in <lg>. Like <div>, <lg> can include a @type attribute to declare its type of grouping; in this example, "poem.sonnet-shakespearean" declares the outer most grouping as a poem, composed in style of Sharespearean sonnet. One could declare this as a ‘poem' or a ‘sonnet,' but we know this to be a Shakespearean sonnet, divided into three <lg>s with a @type of "quatrain" and one <lg> with a type of "couplet". (see for more detail on handling poetry: https://www.wwp.northeastern.edu/research/publications/guide/html/verse_wholepoem.html; for more on the @type attribute for verse see  https://www.wwp.northeastern.edu/research/publications/guide/html/verse_stanzas.html) -->
            <head><!-- poem title or stanza heading --></head>
            <lg type="quatrain" n="1"><!-- the @n attribute may be used to number or count the <lg>s or individual <l>s -->
               <l n="1"/>
               <l n="2"/>
               <l n="3"/>
               <l n="4"/>
            </lg>
            <lg type="quatrain" n="2">
